\begin_layout Subsection
Mixed lineage leukaemia
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Acute leukaemia is typically categorised as either Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "ALL"
description "Acute Lymphoblastic Leukaemia"

\end_inset

ALL) or Acute Myeloid Leukaemia (
\begin_inset CommandInset nomenclature
LatexCommand nomenclature
symbol "AML"
description "Acute Myeloid Leukaemia"

\end_inset

AML) according to which lineage of blood cells are cancerous.
 ALL is defined by the uncontrolled proliferation of lymphoblasts, precursors
 to lymphocytes which differentiate into B cells, T cells and NK cells.
 ALL was estimated to account for approximately 12% of all leukaemia cases
 in the US in 2008 with around five and a half thousand cases occurring
 annually.
 It is the most common form of cancer in children aged under fourteen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AML is a cancer of the myeloid lineages of blood cells, responsible for
 approximately 30% of all cases of leukaemia in the US for 2008 with a higher
 mortality rate than ALL (66% and 27% mortality for AML and ALL, respectively)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
 The incidence of AML increases with age; the median age of AML diagnosis
 between 2002 and 2006 in the US was 67 years, and the median age of mortality
 was 72 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jemal2009"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The biology of leukaemia is not always as discrete as this classification
 however, some patients present with expansion of both lymphoid and myeloid
 lineages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Matutes1997"

\end_inset

.
 Common genetic abnormalities found in these patients include the t(9;22)(q34;q1
1) Philadelphia chromosome and structural changes in 11q23 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Matutes1997"

\end_inset

.
 Chromosomal translocations within band q23 of chromosome 11 have been implicate
d in both AML and ALL, all involve the gene 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 (also known as 
\emph on
ALL-1
\emph default
, 
\emph on
Htrx
\emph default
, 
\emph on
HRX
\emph default
) identified by Ziemin-van der Poel 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 in 1991 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziemin-vanderPoel1991"

\end_inset

.
 Translocations involving the 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 gene are found in over 70% of all infant leukaemias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Biondi2000"

\end_inset

 and approximately 10% of adult AML cases 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Krivtsov2007"

\end_inset

.
 The translocation correlates with poor patient prognosis and is of high
 clinical interest 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chen1993"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In 2002, Armstrong 
\emph on
et al.

\emph default
 showed that acute lymphoblastic leukaemias containing a translocation within
 the 
\emph on
MLL
\emph default
 gene have a unique expression profile that is different to ALL and AML,
 and suggests an origin within a less committed progenitor cell which can
 produce cells in both the myeloid and lymphoid cell lineages 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Armstrong2002"

\end_inset

.
 They suggest that these leukaemias are substantially different from AML
 and ALL and deserve a new, distinct, class of leukaemia called Mixed Lineage
 Leukaemia (MLL).
 Further cytogenetic studies have supported this theory; leukaemic cells
