\begin_layout Subsubsection
Breakage first and contact first models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a chromosomal translocation to form, two double strand breaks must exist
 simultaneously and be adjacent in three-dimensional space.
 Two models have been described to explain how DSBs may meet in the nucleus
 â€“ the breakage first model and the contact first model.
 The breakage first model states that double strand breaks can form anywhere
 and are able to freely diffuse in the nuclear space.
 They undergo large scale movement through the nucleus until they meet and
 are joined.
 The contact first model states that the two double strand breaks form in
 sequences already close to each other within the nuclear space.
 Large scale chromatin movements are not required for the two DSBs to meet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In support of the breakage first model Aten 
\emph on
et al
\emph default
